Censorship is present – and justifiable – in every society. But here is the source of the problem today. We have become so used to the idea that texts are “dirty” that we remove them from public eye and the risk that they may cause social damage is minimal. But the problem is not that certain texts are banned, but rather that they are succeeding in occupying the virtual space, spreading their concept of hate and belonging and shaping the minds of extremist youth.

We live in a world where all information is shared, in which prestigious universities train recruits that leave us to spread the terror and prevent us from taking the same steps forward as other societies.

As Nujeen Musa once said, “War is not fair. It never was, it never will be. I just want peace and a classroom to sit in.”

There has to be a choice and there is a vision and a path to get there: non violence and the IDC is offering a college experience that will give them the requisite tools to have the courage to ask questions and the ‘dedication to difference’ to make the world a more just and tolerant in the near future.

An intelligence official also said that FBI agents discovered in Marwan’s room digital devices that showed footage of attacks at military barracks in Cairo
